Moral Dilemmas for Fannie and Freddie
NEW HAVEN: The takeover of the mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac by the US government represents an enormous bailout of the creditors of these institutions, whose losses had continued to grow due to falling home prices.
Now that the government is fully backing Fannie's and Freddie's debts, American taxpayers will have to pay for everything that is not covered by the insufficient financial resources of their creditors.
Why such a rescue operation in the most overtly capitalist country in the world?
Do the venerable principles of capitalism not include that those who believed in the real estate bubble and invested their money in Fannie and Freddie must now accept their losses?
Is it fair that innocent taxpayers must now bear the consequences of their mistakes?
The answers to these questions would be obvious if the moral problems of the current financial crisis were clearly defined.
But they are not.
First of all, it is unclear whether the bailout will actually cost American taxpayers in the end. It may prevent further systemic effects that would force the financial sector and thus the global economy into collapse.
Just because systemic effects are difficult to quantify does not mean they do not exist.
Moreover, the bonds issued by Fannie and Freddie were widely regarded as being equipped with an implicit guarantee from the US government.
Although there was no official guarantee, the absence of a rescue action by the US government could undermine confidence in government securities—and because they are associated with them—also in other financial instruments.
The problems extend far beyond the US economy.
The global economy has been driven in recent years by remarkable speculative booms and crashes in asset values, bringing questions of trust—and also fairness—into the equation.
Similarly, in many other countries, current booms in the housing sector are coming to an end, and they may face the same struggles—and the same moral dilemmas—that the US economy is currently experiencing.
And the problem are not only the housing markets.
The stock markets are also involved.
The Chinese Shanghai Composite Index rose by a factor of 5 between 2005 and 2007 and then lost two-thirds of its real value.
The Sensex in India rose by a factor of 5 in real terms between 2003 and 2007 and has since lost a third of its value.
Similar booms and crashes in stock markets have occurred in many other countries as well.
As long as they lasted, the boom periods preceding these crashes led to overheating of these economies.
Now that they have reversed, a loss of confidence could grab hold of the global economy and plunge it into recession.
To prevent this, some targeted bailouts may be necessary – not to support the market, but to address injustices.
There is no precise science of trust, no way to predict how people will react when, in the face of collapsing markets, help is withheld.
People's reactions to these events depend on their emotions and their sense of justice.
The described booms and crashes have caused a large redistribution of wealth.
Those who invested in the stock market or the housing market did well or badly depending on timing.
People will judge the fairness of these outcomes based on what was told to them and the implicit promises they derived from it.
What was told to people in all these countries about the markets into which they invested their money?
Did everything really correspond to the truth?
There is unfortunately no way to find out.
Policymakers can only respond generally and cannot treat each case individually.
We know that economic growth in recent times has been spectacular in many countries.
But were capital assets sold at too high a price into their markets?
Have cynical sellers here and elsewhere led people to believe that boom times would bring prosperity for all?
Surely, it is certain that, although there may have been a lot of "cheap talk" – general advice with reservations – most of the losers in this game are not starving.
Yet we cannot casually conclude from this that all their losses should be left untouched.
The nagging problem is one of "trust and faith."
Economies flourish only when "trust and faith" prevail.
The current situation, in which speculative booms have driven the world economy – and now, after their collapse, are driving it into recession – suggests that people who promoted certain capital assets did so against trust and faith.
Take the investors who held bonds from Fannie and Freddie.
Although the US government never officially promised to bail them out, it created a special agency, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, whose task was to assess their strength in an annual report.
This agency never even acknowledged that there was a housing bubble.
Government officials never issued a warning.
Can we really claim that investors must bear all the consequences of their losses?
How could this be fair?
The world is in the process of transforming and discovering the power of capitalism in economies.
Yet capitalism relies on trust and faith.
An unfair treatment can be deadly for economic growth, because it means that people lose their trust in companies and therefore are less willing to provide their valuable capital and their labor.
Is such an outcome morally preferable to a bailout?
